  "prompt": "Is there any organic compound without carbon atom?",
  "response": "No, organic compounds by definition contain carbon atoms. The term \"organic\" in chemistry refers to compounds that contain carbon bonded to hydrogen, and often other elements such as oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and more. \n\nHowever, there are some exceptions where compounds are considered organic despite not containing carbon, but these are extremely rare and typically involve historical or specialized contexts. For example, boron compounds like boranes are sometimes studied in organic chemistry due to their similar reactivity to carbon-based compounds, but they are not technically organic by the strict definition.\n\nIn general, if a compound does not contain carbon, it is classified as an inorganic compound.",
